P L A S T I C P O L L U T I O N
•Plastic pollution is a significant environmental
issue that affects bodies of water worldwide. The
amount of plastic waste being dumped into
oceans, rivers, and lakes daily is equivalent to
2,000 garbage trucks. This pollution has severe
consequences for aquatic ecosystems, as an
estimated 19-23 million tons of plastic waste enters
these ecosystems each year.
H O W D I D T H I S H A P P E N ?
•Plastics made from fossil fuels are just over a century old.
Production and development of thousands of new plastic products
accelerated after World War II, so transforming the modern age that
life without plastics would be unrecognizable today. Plastics
revolutionized medicine with life-saving devices, made space travel
possible, lightened cars and jets—saving fuel and pollution—and
saved lives with helmets, incubators, and equipment for clean
drinking water.
W H Y I S P L A S T I C
P O L L U T I O N I S A P R O B L E M ?
Plastic pollution can alter habitats
and natural processes, reducing
ecosystems’ ability to adapt to
climate change, directly affecting
millions of people’s livelihoods, food
production capabilities and social
well-being.
Human Health Implications
•Moreover, plastics can adsorb and accumulate hazardous
pollutants such as persistent organic pollutants (POPs) and heavy
metals. When ingested, these chemicals can disrupt hormonal
balance, impair organ function, and increase the risk of various
health problems, including reproductive disorders, developmental
abnormalities, and certain cancers.
E D U C A T I O N A N D AW A R E N E S S
•Education and awareness campaigns play a vital role in encouraging responsible
waste management practices and fostering a culture of environmental
stewardship. By adopting sustainable waste management practices and
embracing a circular economy mindset, we can work towards a future where
plastic pollution is minimized, ecosystems are protected, and resources are
conserved for future generations.
H O W C A N W E
S O L V E P L A S T I C
P O L L U T I O N
Plastic pollution can be addressed by
reducing the use of disposable plastics,
supporting legislation to limit plastic
production, proper recycling, using
reusable alternatives, participating in
clean-up efforts, and supporting
organizations working to reduce plastic
pollution.
